title: The Grateful Dead Live at Patrick Gymnasium, U of Vermont on 1983-04-13
description:
Set 1

Jack Straw, They Love Each Other, Beat It On Down The Line, West L.A. Fadeaway, Mama Tried-> Cumberland Blues, Ramble On Rose, Far From Me, My Brother Esau, Might As Well

Set 2

Scarlet Begonias-> Fire On The Mountain, Estimated Prophet-> Eyes Of The World-> Maybe You Know-> Drums-> Morning Dew-> Throwing Stones-> Good Lovin', E: Touch Of Gray

reviews.review_text: Now we're talking... My problem with this show was that both the AUD and SBD sources had significant cuts that really hurt the overall experience.  One cut out in the midst of a monumental final jam in Eyes and the other decided "who really wants to hear an entire Dew of this magnitude?".  Me, that's who.  Good job on this one as usual.  Clear and crisp, not too heavy on the sound of the unwashed masses.  Fantastic show right out of the gate.  Many, many highlights here.  This show has a very well deserved reputation.

Overlooked? Not sure why this show doesn't get more attention and accolades. Great show, awesome set list and energy... not underdone or over cooked... just right, tasty! Jerry misses some lyrics but nails ALL the music and the cadence rocks! Keep coming back to this one, year after year.

THANKS HUNTER!!!

Fuckin A Right. I came here to make noise about this great show, and the well handled slickness that melded the aud and sdb together.. Salutations, Hunter. You've impeccable taste for the vintage Dead. Phil doesn't come through enough would be my main gripe on the sonic notes, but you can't knock this shit folks. Well, you can knock it, but that'd just be some bull clouding your ears and/or brain-pan...

One of the best I was a senior at St Mikes when this show took place and was lucky enough to score a 2nd row ticket in front of Brent from the brother of my girlfriend at the time who was on the SA at UVM. Anyone who was on tour at the time or lived in the Burlington area can relate to how lucky I was to get in that night. 
Amazing show with a killer Scarlett Fire Estimated Eyes and the there is the Dew. 
Miss you Jerry!

Rainbows end down that highway~~ Nice sound here~I like the mix..This show is definitely running under the radar!! Solid from start to finish but not prefect..but what is? I don't seek perfection..This is another one of those venues that was a one and done(another from 83 is Lake Placid) I would have loved the boys to return to Burlington,but like so many places,once the town/city got a taste of the weirdness..we we're not welcome back!!so please>GIVE IT A WHIRL>Forever Grateful>Forever Dead~!!

Good Heavens... This MATRIX is simply incredible. For an '83 recording pool, a product like this in nothing short of remarkable. 

Thank you, Hunter, for taking the time to create this beautiful recording, and for taking the time to share it with us. 
You're most kind.

Perfect sound This is a perfect sounding matrix.
1983 is one of my favorite years, as it was my first.
an amazing MATRIX This is what MATRIX blends were made for. Catching the clarity of a SBD with the visceral physical experience of being there.

Matrix Hello
New to quest to find crackling audio for all shows, especially ones I attended ‘83-95. 
Help me understand/engage MATRIX to make this sonic journey travel forward. 
Thank you and “LEAVE IT ON!”

First Show I attended this show as a freshman Air Force ROTC cadet, and left as a lifelong rider on the bus. Everything was new and bright from the Jack Straw opener, Birdsong flight, Scarlet>Fire>Estimated>Eyes primal beats, and truly transformational Morning Dew. I don't know but I've been told, "it's hard to run with the weight of gold. Otherhand I heard it said, it's just as hard with the weight of lead."

HOLY SCARLET FIRE! This is a long-time favorite in my collection, all the way back to the 80s when I got it on cassette. If there is a better Scarlet-Fire transition out there I have never heard it. This one, after my millionth listen, I can now whistle along with every note of Jerry's magic. 

All that said, if there is a better transition out there I welcome direction as to where to find it.
